				\begin{document}$$u\left(t\right)=\left[{u}_{1}\left(t\right)\ldots {u}_{M}\left(t\right)\right]$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M102"><mml:mi>u</mml:mi><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:mrow><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfenced close="]" open="["><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>u</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:mrow><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced><mml:mo>…</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>u</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:mrow><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="42003_2021_2133_Article_IEq42.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is the associated time-dependent input signal. Cog is a cognitive variable of interest modeled by additive linear relationships, considering the brain’s multifactorial alterations as modulators (with weights defined by the vector <inline-formula id="IEq43"><alternatives><tex-math id="M103">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
